(80, 1, '2019-12-02 23:33:08', '2019-12-02 23:33:08', '<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/220723/pexels-photo-220723.jpeg?auto=format%2Ccompress&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;dpr=2&amp;w=500" alt=""/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Hypertension, virtually asymptomatic, but potentially dangerous, is easy to treat by making the right lifestyle choices and medications. Here are some lifestyle changes you can do to increase your chances of lowering your blood pressure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>Blood pressure in figures:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some 5.5 million Canadians have high blood pressure, but only about 58% are aware of it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In general, experts say that if the blood pressure is in the 140 to 159 mmHg systole or in the 90 to 99 mmHg diastole and it has not responded to changes in lifestyle at After six months to a year, you have to start taking medication.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;If you are able to properly control your blood pressure for a few years, incorporating a lifestyle change into your daily routine, you may be able to get the go-ahead from your doctor to lower the dose of medication or even stop it altogether.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>Diet and blood pressure:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For anyone with mild hypertension, the best thing to do to reduce your blood pressure naturally is to follow the DASH diet and reduce your dietary sodium intake.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;There is a 50% chance that you will have salt-sensitive hypertension, and the more sodium you drink (in the form of table salt and high-sodium foods), the higher your blood pressure will be. Actually, for anyone with hypertension, to reduce their sodium intake below 2400 milligrams a day, can only be beneficial.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;In addition, you need to consume a lot of foods rich in potassium.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is estimated that much of the success of DASH diet is due to the consumption of many foods rich in potassium (like bananas); potassium helps to lower blood pressure by relaxing the arteries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>&nbsp; &nbsp;Stress and blood pressure:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to food, you should also take control of your stress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Even mild tension or anger can increase blood pressure by triggering the release of hormones that compress blood vessels. In addition, stress can be accompanied by depression and anxiety, conditions that can more than double the risk. The best ways to relax are obviously different for each person: it is important to find what works for you and to stick to it. Today, many people relax by doing yoga or yoga. chi. Studies have shown that these Asian and secular exercises lower blood pressure as much as moderate exercise.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>Exercise and blood pressure:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you practice tai chi or cycling, regular exercise is an essential part of any high blood pressure reduction program.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;When you exercise vigorously, you not only increase the well-being hormones called endorphins, but you also reduce stress, anxiety and depression, all in a natural way. By circulating the blood, you contribute to maintain the flexibility of the vessels, which are consequently less subject to a potential narrowing, which is important in maintaining blood pressure. Do not forget to choose aerobic exercises that move the big muscles - walking fast, swimming, cycling - instead of strength exercises (weightlifting), which can temporarily, but significantly, increase blood pressure. And do 30 minutes of exercise for at least three times a week.If you are afraid that exercise increases your blood pressure by more than 20% considered safe, periodically check with a monitor.Coupled with a reasonable diet, exercise aerobic will also help you lose weight, which is good for your health. Being a little overweight doubles the risk of high blood pressure compared to normal weight people. Also, be aware that processed diet drinks and snacks are often loaded with salt to make up for the reduced amount of material. fat and sugar.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Other smart options include sleeping well and sleeping well (lack of sleep speeds up heart rate, which can increase blood pressure) and limiting alcohol and caffeine use. More than one or two alcoholic beverages or 1.25 liters (five cups) of coffee a day can also increase blood pressure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Treating high blood pressure with lifestyle and diet changes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'treating-high-blood-pressure-with-lifestyle-and-diet-changes', '', '', '2020-01-20 15:07:22', '2020-01-20 15:07:22', '', 0, 'https://en.2fun.club/?p=80', 0, 'post', '', 0),
