(768, 1, '2020-03-21 16:03:00', '2020-03-21 16:03:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Every girl wants to&nbsp;be&nbsp;beautiful and attractive. Fortunately, you don’t need to&nbsp;splurge on&nbsp;expensive beauty products to&nbsp;achieve a&nbsp;vibrant look. There are certain effective home remedies that will help you obtain the best results.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We&nbsp;at&nbsp;<strong>Bright Side</strong>&nbsp;have put together 10&nbsp;super simple natural beauty tips that will save you time and money.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>1. A&nbsp;saltwater solution will help reduce swelling and give your face a&nbsp;fresh look.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {"id":767,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://en.2fun.club/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/8160360-kak-bystro-izbavitsja-ot-chernyh-tochek-3-1480531902-650-81a4fdf1c2-1481908582.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-767"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Dissolve salt in&nbsp;water&nbsp;</strong>(the solution should be&nbsp;quite concentrated), soak the towel in&nbsp;the solution, and apply it&nbsp;to&nbsp;your face for 10&nbsp;minutes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>2. Make your lips appear fuller and sexier with an&nbsp;oil and a&nbsp;toothbrush.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Apply any cosmetic oil to&nbsp;your lips&nbsp;— peach oil, almond oil, or&nbsp;regular lip balm. Then&nbsp;<strong>take a&nbsp;soft toothbrush, and rub gently on&nbsp;your lips for 1&nbsp;minute.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>3. Use olive oil to&nbsp;get glowing and moisturized skin.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Massaging your face with olive oil helps to&nbsp;make your skin clean, soft, smooth, and matte.<strong>&nbsp;First, steam your face, and then massage the oil into your face for about 7&nbsp;minutes.&nbsp;</strong>To&nbsp;achieve the best results, repeat the procedure every 4-5&nbsp;days.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>4. Honey can help reduce inflammation and get rid of&nbsp;acne.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If&nbsp;you get a&nbsp;pimple on&nbsp;your face right before a&nbsp;big date or&nbsp;an&nbsp;important meeting, there is&nbsp;a&nbsp;way to&nbsp;get rid of&nbsp;it&nbsp;quickly.<strong>&nbsp;Apply some honey on&nbsp;the acne, and leave it&nbsp;for 15&nbsp;minutes.&nbsp;</strong>Then wash it&nbsp;off with warm water. This method will help you reduce the size of&nbsp;a&nbsp;pimple and make it&nbsp;less noticeable so&nbsp;that you can easily hide it&nbsp;with makeup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>5. Use eye drops to&nbsp;reduce inflammation on&nbsp;your face.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another way to&nbsp;get rid of&nbsp;those pesky pimples is&nbsp;by&nbsp;using eye drops.&nbsp;<strong>Soak a&nbsp;cotton pad in&nbsp;redness-reducing eye drops, and put it&nbsp;in&nbsp;the freezer for 3-5&nbsp;minutes.&nbsp;</strong>Then gently press the cotton pad against the inflamed area, and the pimple will become almost unnoticeable.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>6. All-natural homemade makeup remover.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Mix a&nbsp;3:1 ratio of&nbsp;clean water to&nbsp;olive oil</strong>&nbsp;in&nbsp;a&nbsp;glass jar, and shake it&nbsp;well so&nbsp;that the ingredients combine properly. That’s it!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>7. Baking soda can help get rid of&nbsp;ingrown hair.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This homemade body scrub is&nbsp;really easy to&nbsp;make. In&nbsp;a&nbsp;small bowl,<strong>&nbsp;mix 1&nbsp;teaspoon of&nbsp;baking soda, 1&nbsp;teaspoon of&nbsp;ground oatmeal, and 1&nbsp;tablespoon of&nbsp;water.&nbsp;</strong>Stir well until you get a&nbsp;thick paste. Apply the mixture to&nbsp;the skin, and let it&nbsp;sit for 5&nbsp;minutes. Then rinse with hot water.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>8. Use baking soda to&nbsp;reduce dark circles and bags under the eyes.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Add a&nbsp;teaspoon of&nbsp;baking soda to&nbsp;a&nbsp;glass of&nbsp;hot water or&nbsp;tea, and stir well.</strong>&nbsp;Soak a&nbsp;cotton pad in&nbsp;this mixture, and then apply it&nbsp;to&nbsp;the area under your eyes.&nbsp;<strong>Wait for about 10-15&nbsp;minutes, then wash any residue off and use a&nbsp;moisturizing cream.</strong>&nbsp;Repeat this procedure every day, and you’ll soon notice results!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>9. Banana hair mask for healthy shiny hair.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To&nbsp;prepare this mask you will need:&nbsp;<strong>1&nbsp;banana, 1&nbsp;egg, 1&nbsp;tablespoon of&nbsp;honey, and 1/2 glass of&nbsp;dark beer.&nbsp;</strong>Combine all the ingredients in&nbsp;a&nbsp;small bowl, and stir until smooth. Apply the mixture to&nbsp;your hair for a&nbsp;couple of&nbsp;hours. Then wash it&nbsp;off with warm water. Use this mask once a&nbsp;week, and you’ll see astonishing results very quickly!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>10. Use a&nbsp;coconut and lavender oil mix to&nbsp;grow longer eyelashes.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Combine 1/2 teaspoon of&nbsp;coconut oil with 2&nbsp;to&nbsp;4&nbsp;drops of&nbsp;lavender essential oil.&nbsp;</strong>Using a&nbsp;cotton pad or&nbsp;Q-tip, gently apply the mixture to&nbsp;the lashes, covering them from root to&nbsp;tip. Follow this remedy at&nbsp;least three times a&nbsp;week, and your eyelashes will become thicker and shinier with time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Preview photo credit&nbsp;<a href="http://ru.depositphotos.com/69437869/stock-photo-beauty-concept-skin-care-anti.html?utm_source=Adme&amp;utm_medium=freesub&amp;utm_campaign=RU-brand">depositphotos.co</a>m</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Source: brightside.me</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '752-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-03-21 16:03:00', '2020-03-21 16:03:00', '', 752, 'https://en.2fun.club/752-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(148, 1, '2019-12-04 15:22:44', '2019-12-04 15:22:44', '<!-- wp:image {"id":872,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://en.2fun.club/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/disease-4392162_1280-1024x682.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-872"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During the winter months, three-quarters of the population suffer from this mild respiratory disease caused by a virus. Except in case of superinfection, it heals spontaneously in one week. Colds of viral origin should not be confused with hay fever or allergic rhinitis.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>What are the symptoms of colds?&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The runny and stuffy nose, as well as sneezing, are the most unpleasant and common symptoms of a common cold (commonly known as a common cold). The liquid which flows is at first clear; it often becomes thicker and purulent after a few days. At that moment, the nose is easily clogged. Other symptoms are common, a tickle or even a burning sensation in the nose, a loss of smell and taste more or less pronounced, even fever.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>In children, colds are most often rhinopharyngitis.</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;Some people have problems with chronic rhinitis (repeated colds or persistent rhinitis). In most cases, this chronic rhinitis is perennial allergic rhinitis. Nevertheless, it happens that this form of rhinitis has a different cause. This is referred to as non-allergic vasomotor rhinitis, or chronic inflammatory rhinitis. In this case, it is often an imbalance of the nervous system that controls the nasal mucosa. It becomes hypersensitive and reacts to many factors (stress, weather, polluted or smoky atmospheres, etc.) by triggering fluid secretion and sneezing. The misuse of local vasoconstrictor drugs (sprays to unclog the nose) exposes this type of rhinitis. Chronic rhinitis sometimes occurs during pregnancy, probably related to the hormonal changes that occur in pregnant women.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What are the causes of colds?&nbsp;</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The nasal fossae and the sinuses are lined with a mucosa that continuously secretes a liquid. This liquid humidifies the inspired air, traps dust and helps fight against infectious agents. When this mucosa is irritated, it swells and its secretion increases, so that the nose flows. It is the cold (rhinitis or coryza). The viruses that are responsible for it are transmitted from one person to another, most often by hands or contaminated objects.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>What are the possible complications of colds?&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The simple cold usually evolves towards uncomplicated healing. When the mucosa is strongly inflamed or the natural defenses diminished, other respiratory diseases may occur in the upper lanes (tracheitis, bronchitis), the sinuses or the middle ear. Infections can then settle and cause various diseases, such as sinusitis or otitis.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>What to do in case of colds?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;It is claimed that a cold "lasts seven days without treatment, one week with treatment". To tell the truth, there is neither vaccine nor medicine against the very numerous viruses of the cold. However, some measures can reduce the unpleasant symptoms: - drink a lot (at least 1.5 to two liters a day); - get enough sleep - moisten your nasal mucosa with saline or by inhalation; - take an antipyretic and analgesic medicine to fight fever and headaches.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>How to prevent colds?&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dress warmly during the cold season. Regularly ventilate the rooms (even in winter) and humidify the surrounding air if necessary. This can improve the resistance of the nasal mucosa. Exercise, sports practice is an important element to keep a good physical shape. Some people take vitamin C (fruit juice, oranges, lemons, kiwis, vitamin preparations) that would strengthen the natural defenses. Scientific evidence is lacking to confirm this hypothesis.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>Cold treatments&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In many cases, taking an analgesic medicine may be sufficient. Otherwise, there are many over-the-conter medications that work on the symptoms. Some contain: - an analgesic antipyretic drug that lowers fever and relieves headaches associated with colds; an antihistaminic drug of the H1 type which has a drying effect on the secretion of mucus; - a vasoconstrictor drug that has a decongestant effect, giving the feeling of breathing more freely.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> The use of these drugs requires certain precautions related to the effects of the various substances they contain. For example, drugs containing an antihistamine can cause drowsiness, which can be severe in some people. Those containing a vasoconstrictor should not be used without medical advice in people with narrow-angle glaucoma or prostate adenoma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> They can increase the heart rate (tachycardia), and cause palpitations. If these side effects become too pronounced, treatment should be discontinued. Local treatments can also clear the nose: saline, antibacterial nasal solution, inhalations.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Cold symptoms and treatment methods', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cold-symptoms-and-treatment-methods', '', '', '2020-04-23 12:14:10', 