llergic vasomotor rhinitis, or chronic inflammatory rhinitis. In this case, it is often an imbalance of the nervous system that controls the nasal mucosa. It becomes hypersensitive and reacts to many factors (stress, weather, polluted or smoky atmospheres, etc.) by triggering fluid secretion and sneezing. The misuse of local vasoconstrictor drugs (sprays to unclog the nose) exposes this type of rhinitis. Chronic rhinitis sometimes occurs during pregnancy, probably related to the hormonal changes that occur in pregnant women.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What are the causes of colds?&nbsp;</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The nasal fossae and the sinuses are lined with a mucosa that continuously secretes a liquid. This liquid humidifies the inspired air, traps dust and helps fight against infectious agents. When this mucosa is irritated, it swells and its secretion increases, so that the nose flows. It is the cold (rhinitis or coryza). The viruses that are responsible for it are transmitted from one person to another, most often by hands or contaminated objects.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>What are the possible complications of colds?&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The simple cold usually evolves towards uncomplicated healing. When the mucosa is strongly inflamed or the natural defenses diminished, other respiratory diseases may occur in the upper lanes (tracheitis, bronchitis), the sinuses or the middle ear. Infections can then settle and cause various diseases, such as sinusitis or otitis.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>What to do in case of colds?</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;It is claimed that a cold "lasts seven days without treatment, one week with treatment". To tell the truth, there is neither vaccine nor medicine against the very numerous viruses of the cold. However, some measures can reduce the unpleasant symptoms: - drink a lot (at least 1.5 to two liters a day); - get enough sleep - moisten your nasal mucosa with saline or by inhalation; - take an antipyretic and analgesic medicine to fight fever and headaches.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>How to prevent colds?&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dress warmly during the cold season. Regularly ventilate the rooms (even in winter) and humidify the surrounding air if necessary. This can improve the resistance of the nasal mucosa. Exercise, sports practice is an important element to keep a good physical shape. Some people take vitamin C (fruit juice, oranges, lemons, kiwis, vitamin preparations) that would strengthen the natural defenses. Scientific evidence is lacking to confirm this hypothesis.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->\n<h3>Cold treatments&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In many cases, taking an analgesic medicine may be sufficient. Otherwise, there are many over-the-conter medications that work on the symptoms. Some contain: - an analgesic antipyretic drug that lowers fever and relieves headaches associated with colds; an antihistaminic drug of the H1 type which has a drying effect on the secretion of mucus; - a vasoconstrictor drug that has a decongestant effect, giving the feeling of breathing more freely.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> The use of these drugs requires certain precautions related to the effects of the various substances they contain. For example, drugs containing an antihistamine can cause drowsiness, which can be severe in some people. Those containing a vasoconstrictor should not be used without medical advice in people with narrow-angle glaucoma or prostate adenoma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> They can increase the heart rate (tachycardia), and cause palpitations. If these side effects become too pronounced, treatment should be discontinued. Local treatments can also clear the nose: saline, antibacterial nasal solution, inhalations.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Cold symptoms and treatment methods', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '148-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-12-04 15:18:12', '2019-12-04 15:18:12', '', 148, 'https://en.2fun.club/?p=156', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
